Sorry, I am aware the answer is accepted. &lt;br&gt;But I think, I can provide a little bit insight and obtain a little bit of healthy criticism :&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
The MenuInflater is an *Android system resource*. It is created when the android boots up. It is a persistent object and the reference to it is always available in memory. &lt;br/&gt;
Every subclass of Context class *i.e. Activity* in your case, can obtain the reference to it, by calling:  
1. ```getMenuInflater()``` from within the class(Example: **Context**) or any of its subclass(Ex: **Activity**)
2. ```&lt;any_context_object&gt;.getMenuInflater()``` from outside the class. 
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;

# Internally:
```getMenuInflater()``` checks if a MenuInflater object exists in memory and then :
- If it does exist in memory , it returns the object. 
- Otherwise, it creates one, and returns it. 

It is called a Singleton design pattern and ensures that one and only one instance of a class is created. In doing so, you can reuse the state of the old object and share that state across multiple processes without explicitly passing it to them.

So, Android Runtime creates one MenuInflater object and applications can ask for it by calling the getMenuInflater() method defined on the context object.


``` java
public MenuInflater getMenuInflater() {
    // Make sure that action views can get an appropriate theme.
    if (mMenuInflater == null) {
        initWindowDecorActionBar();
        if (mActionBar != null) {
            mMenuInflater = new MenuInflater(mActionBar.getThemedContext(), this);
        } else {
            mMenuInflater = new MenuInflater(this);
        }
    }
    return mMenuInflater;
}
 ```

